Step 1: Create Personal Access Token in GitLab

Open your browser and go to your GitLab URL

   https://gitlab.yourcompany.com
Login through Okta (the normal way you always do)
Once logged in, click your profile picture (top-right corner)
Click "Edit profile" or "Preferences"
In the left sidebar, find and click "Access Tokens"
Click "Add new token" button
Fill in the form:

   Name: mac-vscode-git
   Expiration date: (choose a date, e.g., 1 year from now)
   
   Select scopes (check these boxes):
   âœ… api
   âœ… read_repository  
   âœ… write_repository
Click "Create personal access token"
CRITICAL: A token will appear like this:

   glpat-abc123xyz789...
Copy it immediately! You won't be able to see it again.

Save it somewhere safe (password manager, notes app - you'll need it)


Step 2: Configure Git on Your Mac
Open Terminal app and run:
# Set your name (use your real name)
git config --global user.name "John Doe"

# Set your email (use your work email)
git config --global user.email "john.doe@company.com"

# Tell Git to use macOS Keychain to save credentials
git config --global credential.helper osxkeychain

Step 3: Clone Repository (First Time Authentication)

# Navigate to where you want your code
cd ~/Documents  # or wherever you want

# Clone your repository
git clone https://gitlab.yourcompany.com/team-name/repo-name.git
```

**You'll be prompted:**
```
Username for 'https://gitlab.yourcompany.com': 
```
â†’ Type your **GitLab username** (usually your email or username)
```
Password for 'https://username@gitlab.yourcompany.com':
 Paste your Personal Access Token (the one you copied in Step 1)

Verify it's saved:

# Try pulling code
cd repo-name
git pull
```

If it doesn't ask for credentials again â†’ âœ… Success! Credentials are saved.

